Lab 8 - Model Training and Evaluation¶

Author: Kevin Paganini
Date: 2/5/2023
Description: In this lab we are analyzing a stroke dataset. Included in the features we have an id, gender age, hypertension, heart_disease, ever_married, work_type, Residence_type, avg_glucose_level, bmi, smoking_status. Stroke is the dependent variable. Most variables are categorical, however we do have three features that are continuous. In this notebook I import the dataset, cleaned the dataset, did visualizations and statistical tests and then tried out various different models. Once I found the best model with the best combination of features I retrained this model on the entire dataset.

# makes plots nice
def make_pretty(ax, title='', x_label='', y_label='', img=False):
    ax.set_title(title, fontsize=20)
    ax.set_xlabel(x_label, fontsize=16)
    ax.set_ylabel(y_label, fontsize=16)
    ax.legend(loc='best', fontsize=16)
    if img:
        ax.axis('off')
    return ax


stroke_path = os.path.join('Data', 'healthcare-dataset-stroke-data-1.csv')

The columns are as follows:
• id: unique identifier
• gender: "Male", "Female" or "Other"
• age: age of the patient
• hypertension: 0 if the patient doesn't have hypertension, 1 if the patient has
hypertension
• heart_disease: 0 if the patient doesn't have any heart diseases, 1 if the patient has a heart disease
• ever_married: "No" or "Yes"
• work_type: "children", "Govt_jov", "Never_worked", "Private" or "Self-employed"
• Residence_type: "Rural" or "Urban"
• avg_glucose_level: average glucose level in blood
• bmi: body mass index
• smoking_status: "formerly smoked", "never smoked", "smokes" or "Unknown"*
• stroke: 1 if the patient had a stroke or 0 if not

1. Exploratory Data Analysis¶

It is likely smoking_status will be a good predictor of stroke. I also could see hypertension being a good predictor of strokes as well. I am unsure, but maybe there is a difference in male / female strokes. Maybe males tend to have more strokes than females. Heart_disease can be a good predictor as well. I think we have a lot of good date to work with here. I think a lot of the features here should have good association with stroke.

Statistical Tests¶

In [ ]:
from scipy.stats import kruskal


cont_var = ['avg_glucose_level', 'bmi', 'age']


for x in cont_var:
    samples_by_group = []
    for y in set(df['stroke']):
        mask = df['stroke'] == y
        samples_by_group.append(df[x][mask]) 
    stat, p = kruskal(*samples_by_group, nan_policy='omit')
        
    


    print(f'{x} p: {p}')
    print(f'{x} stat: {stat}')

avg_glucose_level stat: 34.80739568673386
bmi p: 0.00010263237377217097
bmi stat: 15.087653240803583
age p: 3.695033198300678e-71
age stat: 318.13281444188146

Interestingly enough bmi has the highest p value.

from scipy.stats import chi2_contingency

cat_vars = ['gender', 'hypertension', 'heart_disease', 'ever_married', 'work_type', 'Residence_type', 'smoking_status']



for val in cat_vars:
    comb_counts = pd.crosstab(df[val], df['stroke'])
    chi2, p, _, _ = chi2_contingency(comb_counts)
    
    print(f'{val} chi2: {chi2}')
    print(f'{val} p: {p}')

3. Choice of evaluation metric and baseline model¶

Since both false negatives and false positives are both costly, we want to use a metric that takes both into account. Therefore, I will be using the f1-score. The f1-score is the harmonic mean of the precision and recall. 2 * (precision * recall) / (precision + recall)

Making a dummy classifier¶

In [ ]:
from sklearn.dummy import DummyClassifier
from sklearn.metrics import f1_score

dummy = DummyClassifier(strategy='constant', constant=1)
dummy.fit(X_train, y_train)
f1_score(y_train, dummy.predict(X_train))
Out[ ]:
0.08748538011695906

Gotta beat an f1 score of 0.087 for it to actually be doing something.

Making a preprocessing pipeline¶

In [ ]:
from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline
from sklearn.impute import SimpleImputer
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.compose import ColumnTransformer
from sklearn.preprocessing import OneHotEncoder
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression


num_attribs = ['age', 'bmi', 'avg_glucose_level']
cat_attribs = ['gender', 'hypertension', 'heart_disease', 'ever_married', 'work_type', 'Residence_type', 'smoking_status']


num_pipeline = Pipeline([
    ('imputer', SimpleImputer(strategy='median')),
    ('std_scaler', StandardScaler())
])

full_pipe = Pipeline([
    ('preprocessor', ColumnTransformer([
        ('num', num_pipeline, num_attribs),
        ('cat', OneHotEncoder(), cat_attribs)
    ]))
])
In [ ]:
full_pipe_log_reg = Pipeline([('full_pipe', full_pipe), ('log_reg', LogisticRegression(solver='lbfgs', max_iter=1000, penalty='l2', C=1.0))])

best = 0
count = 1
scores = []
lgs = [age, bmi, avg_glucose_level, gender, hypertension, heart_disease, married, job, house, smoking]
lgs_names = ['age', 'bmi', 'avg_glucose_level', 'gender', 'hypertension', 'heart_disease', 'married', 'job', 'house', 'smoking']
for lg in lgs:
    scores.append(np.mean(lg['test_score']))

ret = np.argsort(scores)
ret = ret
print(f'Best indices sorted in lowest score to highest score: {ret}')
for i in ret:
    print(f'{lgs_names[i]} : {scores[i]}')

The most predictive feature was age. When looking at the violin plot of age one saw a big difference between stroke and no stroke. Only older people suffered strokes. Heart_disease is also a common precursor to strokes as well as hypertension (stress). It also makes sense that gender as well as bmi are the worst predictors. Strokes affect genders the same and bmi has been debunked many times before as an inaccurate measurement. The only suprising thing to me is smoking being less predictive than married and job categories. Maybe the saying happy wife happy life is true after all.
